input_doc: Nice restaurant, friendly staff, good solid food. They were able to make me a mocktail (since I'm preggo). My husband got a steak and ate the whole plate clean. My mom got prime rib and loved it. I got the chicken Parmesan which was super tasty. Shrimp cocktail for appetizer, lobster bisque $ Caesar salad were good. Key lime pie for dessert was yummmmmy! Would return.

The food here is fabulous!!! don't judge by the appearances; it's in a small strip mall & very limited seating w/virtually no ambiance. Prices are more than you would expect given the appearance but the food is truly top shelf New England style seafood. Lobster Rolls, full belly clams and clam strips are our favs along with the unbelievable NE Clam Chowder. This little place is a genuine culinary find!

Datz is great, I've eaten here twice and mainly wanted to come back to try the donuts! THEY'RE A MUST!

I've also had their gigantic hot chocolate which is sooooo good...I clearly have a sweet tooth) and another item that's no longer on the menu, but it was good as well.

Basically go, you won't be disappointed!

input_doc:
I spent many saturdays walking here with my folks to shop and eat breakfast...  I still go every time I'm in Philthy to gets my grub on.

Harry Ochs - Best Butcher in the world

Amish Breakfasts - Ummm scrapple and pancakes

Amish sticky buns - No raisins please, get these at the Amish bakery or at the breakfast stand.  Hands down best baked good in the world - Tartine's morning buns are a distant second

DeNic's - My favorite sammie in the galaxy is the roast pork, all garlicy and nice - with aged provolone and peppers

Birch Beer - Homebrew from the Amish, sweet!

Just about anything at Delilahs...

Down Home Diner and Jack McDavid - Because you made fun of Bobby Flay years before it became fashionable!  

And all the rest of youse there....

They have the best lunch buffet regarding Indian food and it's around $10 dollars. Derive is always polite and the food is soooooooooo good! If you like spicy food then you must try the chicken or lamb vindaloo!!! Thank me later.

input_doc:
First, this restaurant is a bit of a cross between a stop-in Chinese joint (numbered meals on the wall) and an American "family restaurant". There are a few tables and the waiter/cook will take your order and bring you food tableside. Ambiance is not exotic or impressive, however - the food is fresh and delish!
I had the chicken shawarma platter and picked rice and baba ganouj for the sides. The baba was very smooth and smoky - exactly what you would expect and you get a TON of chicken and rice (got two meals out if it) plus a large pita comes with the meal. I wanted grape leaves - they only do a full order - but they roll them there and they are delish - so it was worth it!
All in all, not fancy, but very yummy.  Mmmmm shawarma...

input_doc: If you want what just might be the best burger you have ever had, you need to try this place! I am a child of the 60's from Chicago. My Grandfather and Dad took us to places like this all the time. No frills, great atmosphere, service and food at a reasonable price. Our beer was served in frozen, heavy old goblet glasses of my past. We had double cheeseburgers, fried mushrooms and onion rings, all served in red plastic baskets lined with deli paper. Our server asked us if we had been there before. We had not so she gave us a brief menu tour. The menu is on an old board on the wall. input_doc: My husband and I were traveling,very tired and SUPER hungry we saw Legends sign off the interstate. We were so pleased with everything. The service was efficient and friendly. our steaks were cook as we ask them and the mashed potatoes were soooo good I ask for a side to go. The salad bar was very fresh. When we travel back to Nashville we will definitely eat at Legends again! Try it for your self!

This is our go to Chinese take out. The dinner combinations are only available for take out... So when dining in you do not receive a chocho or fried rice- only white rice. Well goooood Lawd it was twice the amount of chicken I normally get in my take out I didn't even touch the rice. I enjoyed my piña colada and the won ton soup was the best I have ever had. 

I have enough chicken for two more meals from one $12 entree. My SO had left overs for an extra meal as well which is rare! So portions are huge! We agreed to share an entree next time we go.

input_doc: Royal Chef has continuously been one of the best Chinese Takeouts in Ewing.  They have been around for suuuuuper long and it is obvious why.  The food is tasty, the portions are generous, plus it is owned by a really nice family.  Honestly you get the best bang for your buck here.

Leaving this review solely to make up for the shocking lack of Brie-stuffed French Toast w/ Apricot glaze love in these comments. Get the Brie-stuffed French Toast w/ Apricot Glaze and a coffee, and sit on the patio when it's nice out - you will not regret it!!!! I branch out sometimes but always return to the Brie French Toast. Top 3 Favorite brunch item in the city I've tried. I still consider myself a regular here even though it's been months. Friendly staff, always great service, cash only but the ATM on-site won't derail your brunching. Small space gets crowded sometimes but they're never too overwhelmed to take care of you. input_doc: Awesome dogs!!! They have little slider type hot dogs that they call Puppy Dogs! my 7 year old and husband love them lol

I've driven by here many times & wanted to stop but parking is horrible in the area. Well one day the stars aligned & I happen to be driving by and there was a spot right across from here. I stopped in & picked a few treats. I really wanted to try a Napoleon for the 1st time but was told they're only made on Fridays. I tried some kind of pear tart which was absolutely divine along with some other treats. Will def be back!!!

OMG! Sooo good. I don't know where to begin! It all starts with these garlicy cornbreads, and moves on to some tasty, tasty, tasty cajun cooking. input_doc:
This is our absolute favorite spot on the Hill, I have no idea how I haven't written a review before now! We jokingly call it our "Applebees" because it's our local spot that we can always agree on and never disappoints. Their pastas are amazing (try the pink sauce!), they have two of my favorite salads in the city (the kale caesar and the house), and all their appetizers are sooo good. Some nights we just do appetizers, which usually consists of t-ravs, baked goat cheese and spanakopita, though sometimes we mix it up. They also have the nicest servers ever!! Seriously, these girls rock. 

Since COVID, we have only been doing takeout and have consistently had really great food every time (and we eat here at least once a month, if not more). They do offer curbside, but since dine-in has reopened and the Hill has gotten busier, it's easier to just run in and get our food. They are offering indoor dining and have adjusted the dining room to fit restrictions, but we aren't comfortable eating inside anyplace, so it's nice that we always know we're getting good food when we order takeout from here.

input_doc: Can't say enough how delicious this place is!!!! If you love biscuits then this has to be a stop on your way through Nashville. We went on a Monday night and there was a small wait but it was well worth it! The best fried chicken I have ever had not to be out done by the amazing BBQ pork and fried catfish. Our waiter was extremely friendly and made the experience even better. Truly like having dinner at grandma's!!!

This place? YES! Eat here! I got a rib eye, and it was cooked to PERFECTION! I personally am not a huge fan of as much char as they have on their meats, but this place is literally called a "CHAR-B-QUE," I can't knock any points down for that. They also have barbecue sauces on the side that were soooo good! Try them all!

This was my first time going and I can't wait to go back! They've got burgers, burritos, and more! I'm definitely getting a burrito next time! Yum!

input_doc: Sooo good. I had the jambalaya pasta with the gator sausage and shrimp in it and it was pretty good. But I'm definitely sticking with the gumbo!

I'm not sure what the difference between a Brooklyn style pizza and Sicilian but regardless I was happy to have so many options. Under specialty pizzas they had everything from vegetable lovers, bacon chicken ranch, taco, even a chicken fajita pizza! These people are awesome!!!

input_doc: Good food and great place, but the service can be a little spotty.  It was busy, so I'm only going to deduct one star.  But for all you waiters and waitresses out there, don't let a glass get empty before asking if you want another!!!!

Simply put, it's our favorite place to have beignets and coffee in all of New Orleans. FAR BETTER than Cafe du Monde in every way! Great service (especially the nice kid with floppy hair, he's super sweet!), amazing beignets, great coffee, very reasonable prices, and wonderful ambiance both inside with acoustic guitar in the evenings or outside on the gorgeous, shaded private patio. With street performers on the other side of the patio's wrought iron fence, it allows you to see and hear everything well but the fence assures you aren't heckled for money and don't need to worry too much about safety. input_doc: I agree w Dan R. All of this fawning over decor and servers misses the point. Food portions small, not elegantly presented and waaay over-priced. These Main Line doyens are easily fooled. I'm from NJ- fahgetaboutit.

Drinks that I have had here that I love include The Claret Cup and The Grand Marnier Splash.  Just fantastic!! They have small plate offerings and artisanal cheeses. input_doc: I go here weekly. Sooooo yummy. Fries are the best. My favorites are the burgers and the Rachel sandWich.

We go there just to buy tuna and salmon for sushi/poke and I have been told on occasion that the fish was not to be used raw which meant I didn't buy it on those couple occasions.  Lost a sale, but gained a loyal, long term customer. 

  You too can make sushi at home!  It's waaayyyy less expensive than eating out and, honestly, the fish from Trader Bay is of better quality than any of our local sushi restaurants. Ask for sushi quality tuna and fresh Scottish salmon (Thursday afternoon is the best time to go!)

input_doc:
The name of this restaurant is so fitting- you feel right at home when you come here! The food was great, but I think what we loved most was the hospitality and eclectic atmosphere. 

We came for brunch on a gorgeous patio-worthy day, and we were happy to find a good sized patio! If it's not a patio day, the inside is so cool with all of these antique items on the shelves and gosh it smells good in there. Our cashier was helpful and the definition of hospitality. We decided on the biscuits & gravy and the blueberry pancakes with lemon curd, a special that day. Both were great! I also got a cold brew coffee which was sooo good and my husband got a mimosa, and I think that was the best thing we got! They fresh squeeze their orange juice, and you can tell.

10/10 recommend for brunch, and I'd like to come try dinner!

I LOVE this place! I came here once to switch up my normal Starbucks study sessions, and try somewhere new...needless to say, I've been back several times since!

The inside is so spacious and welcoming, the wifi is free? the owners and their staff are extremely friendly and helpful, and their dessert selection is not only impressive, but from what I've tried so far, they're also very well made! I get the Café Bombón to drink (half espresso shots, half sweetened condensed milk), and it is the most perfect, sweet, creamy pick-me-up you could ask for! For dessert, I've tried their banana pudding (to DIE for), their Chocolate Pot du Jour (a luxuriously smooth dark chocolate/espresso custard), and the Chocolate Peanut Butter Cream Pie (again, another winner!)

input_doc: The brisket poutine is a must!!! Everything I've tried from Sterling Pig was phenomenal. The meats just melt in your mouth. The piggy bread is amazing and I'm not even a huge cinnamon fan. Also highly recommend their Big Gunz Double IPA.

Love the food. And love the décor - very mid-century meets industrial . E+D (Eat and Drink) and its "sister"-restaurant, Taste Cafe and Marketplace, are my regular "go-to" Indianapolis restaurants because their food is consistent (exactly the same and equally delicious every time) and consistently great. I ordered the tinga tacos tonight; they did not disappoint.

input_doc:
this place was a let down

i came in for lunch and we waited about 5 minutes for a host to come up but it wasn't busy at all, i guess they just didn't have a lot of workers that day. i could tell by the few tables that were occupied that they were also waiting for their waiters

once we got seated i ordered the french onion soup, a breakfast sandwich w/ porkroll. my friend got sweet potato fries and the duck quesadilla

french onion soup - cheese was good but the soup itself was suuuper bland. not worth it for the price, i've had much better

breakfast sandwich w/ porkroll - this was so so, not worth it for the price again. i can get it for $5 at the deli near my apartment for better quality. the egg was not well cooked and the bread was stale. the breakfast potatoes were also bland and not warm

the sweet potato fries were probably the most decent thing i ate here. the service was mediocre and the restaurant itself was pretty small and empty, something needs to happen!

input_doc:
Honestly this is the best asian food in Reno.  I was born and raised in Hawaii (the asian mixing bowl of the pacific) and been all over Asian in my travels and I have to say that Pho Mein has really hit it on the head for great tasting and authentic asian food!  The Vietnamese and Chinese dishes are perfect, fast, hot, and taste rediculously good (better than the holes in the wall in Hawaii too!).

I HIGHLY recommend this place to anyone coming to Reno and in the need for asian food.  The noodles are awesome and the duck in superb, the broth and the light sauces are fantastic!  Im sooooo glad I found this place in Reno (which is definitely not known for its asian fare).  It looks very "typically" mainland interpretation of an asian restaurant, which is why I didn't want to eat there for a long time, but I just happened to be there and be hungry one night and it changed my eating schedule permanently!

I eat there often now and have yet to have a bad/slow/bland meal, and the service is phenomenal and the prices are very reasonable.

input_doc: 1st time customer. Sooo yummy. I ate the  samosas in the car they smelled so good. The palak paneer and rice was delicious as well. I ordered to go  and it was ready very quickly. I will definitely  be back!

input_doc: Awesome place!! The food is fast and amazing!!! I haven't had curry this good in a long time!!!

If ever you've been confused by a review of mine where I gave a popular restaurant with high ratings a low star review... then come to Tito's and see why!!!

So far I've only tried the CHURRASCO SKIRT STEAK PLATE ($14) with yellow rice, but I honestly don't know if I will ever try anything else because it was SOOOO GOOD! Seasoned by angels and cooked with such perfection that I will absolutely crave this for the rest of my life! THIS, my dear Yelp people, is EXACTLY what I mean by "flavorful" seasoning. They have completely ruined skirt steak cooked by anyone else because I can't go back to anything less than this level of satisfaction! Even the Strawberry Banana Smoothie ($6) is excellent!

Tito's is currently located in an empty lot next to the Citgo Gas Station on the corner of North Jones Ave and West Waters Street, but this is also the location of their soon to be brick & mortar restaurant. So if you love New York style Puerto Rican cuisine, rush here as soon as possible and taste heaven on a plate!

input_doc:
I've been getting pizza from Sal's for over a decade and didn't realize just how awesome it was until I moved to Boston and couldn't find a decent slice ANYWHERE. Seems like your standard neighborhood joint, but they really make some top notch pizzas. Plenty of sauce and cheese, but never greasy like the chain places (Pizza Hut, Domino's, etc.). I looooooooove their steak pizza, which features a heaping portion of crispy shaved steak.

Sal's is definitely my go-to over other local places like Fiesta, Roman Delight, Roslyn Pizza, etc.. Only reason I didn't give them five stars is because I haven't had anything else off of their menu, but the pizza is certainly worthy of a perfect rating.

input_doc:
I've been here twice - once for dinner and then another time for late night desserts/drinks. I've tried many times to get a seat at their happy hour but have not met success so I would definitely recommend getting there early since I believe you have to sit at the bar.

(+) lobster chow fun - I'm a huge fan of the thick rice noodles so I was very excited for this! The lobster was tender and there was a good amount and the flavor/texture of the noodles was really yummy. The addition of jicama made the dish unique.
(neutral) edamame dumplings - while they were soft and the broth was tasty, I've had edamame dumplings done better at other spots and for a cheaper price
(neutral) mapo tofu - a twist on the typical mapo tofu appetizer, they had crisps on the top of diced tofu pieces - definitely didn't taste bad but tasted veryyyyy different from the traditional mapo tofu so I'm not sure if I would order it again
(+) icecream sushi - a really fun dish to order with friends and has a great chocolate sauce!

input_doc: Absolutely love this place! It has a great atmosphere and a great couple running the place. They were super friendly and gave us great advice on some fun attractions in the city. If I lived in St. Louis I would go here every day for breakfast... And probably lunch!!!

Do yourself a favor and sit at the bar/tiki area. Yeah, the fish tank is cool, but it's easy to see that before/after dinner. The live music at the bar and the fresh air are a nice, laid-back environment. Jenn, our server, was fantastic. She was attentive, friendly, and offered suggestions based on our preferences (and the 3 of us we aren't easy: 1 pescatarian with allergies, 1 lactose intolerant, and 1 vegetarian). The food was AMAZING. In fact, we sat down at a bar for food tonight (after going to Rumfish last night) and after no one came to our table to get a drink order, we got up and walked half a mile to Rumfish to have a second dinner there. We loved the cioppano, burrata salad, grouper, and cheese tortellini. The fried calamari appetizer is also soooo good. Yum! Fresh fresh fresh!!! That's the operative word here for this restaurant!
I'm giving my review based solely on the sushi we ate last night and Sakura has some of the freshest sushi I have eaten...and that's saying a lot as I've been coast to coast in the United States! I have had bad sushi in coastal areas (where the sushi quality should have been excellent) and I have had great
Sushi in inland areas (where I expected the sushi to be bad). Sakura was one of the places where I expected bad quality sushi but was so blown away by the freshness and great taste of the sushi that I had to give this hidden gem my honest review.

input_doc: I ordered the smoked turkey and avocado sandwich, with a side of potato salad SO SOOOO GOOD ! The taste all together of the potato salad is a MUST try when at the butcher. We had a rental car to drive so fairly easy parking, if ridding the street cars use green line to garden district and be prepared to walk a little ways to get here, but worth it! On the way out the door I got a pecan cookie which again was another WIN WIN! If your wanting something besides seafood while in NOLA head the the butcher and get some awesome tasty meats! (Pork sliders my mom had were the BOMB too!)

I am absolutely obsessed with this place! I am a college freshman at Villanova this year and despite hearing all the horror stories about dining hall food, nothing could possibly have prepared me for how bad it would actually be. Thankfully, I quickly found this place since it's literally less than a minute's walk away from my dorm, and I could not be more impressed with both the quality of food and the customer service. It's already been almost a month into my first semester of college and I have already been to this place countless times and each time the employees have been so friendly to me and I always say hello to the owner who is also so kind. I will say that it does take some time before getting your food, but it doesn't bother me much considering how fresh and hot my food comes out. It is also worth mentioning that the amount of food they give you is RIDICULOUSLY huge which makes it a great deal for the price, especially since it's delicious. My go-to order is almost always a (not so) small order of mozzarella fries with gravy, and as someone who has eaten authentic Canadian poutine multiple times, I can easily say that this comes very close to tasting like the real thing. If you're expecting to come here on the weekend I would recommend making a reservation. Today I had a large party of 8 and even after checking the website I did not believe we needed to make reservations. 

The host recommended to come back after 4 not even asking if we wanted to add our party to the waitlist, this led me to believe the establishment was reservations only. She also suggested we order to go. 

Hmmm at this point it was our best option. We head over to the bar to order. The bartender/server was not nice or attentive. We ordered the Voodoo rice and the portion was definitely small for a rice appetizer. I'm pretty sure we had more cheese than rice.

This is an ageless restaurant!  This is the stuff that crawls in your pants and can give the Scroogest of Scrooges in the belly! I love this place - no more than 50 other outstanding places in Nola, but just try to find a bad meal in this town (you can't do it.... Go ahead, try to find a bad meal). 

Love the rabbit here, but it chases me for another day because it's soooo rich - there's lots of Brennan's Restaurants in Nola (and I don't know which ones are part of which side of the family) they fight like Hatfield's and McCoy's, to bad they can't get along. By the way... They ruined "Breakfast at Brennan's".

Love the BBQ shrimp here but it's not quite Pascal Manale's - the lovely dinning room at Mr. B's makes it a close call (don't get me wrong the BBQ shrimp here is awesome) but when I'm at Mr B's I get the rabbit. 

Mmmmmm' Mr. B's (live life and eat here) at least once - also: I don't believe the the $$$ - it cost more than that, but I'm a drinker and this cost the same as going to any other 4 star resturant

input_doc:
I was craving some steak, but was not wanting to spend the money or dress up for St. Elmo's or the Ruth's...   

I ordered one of their "favorite" flank steak, and was cooked exactly how i wanted. (medium rare) I sub the mashed with spinach, and was great. I would've gave 5 if the food didn't take too long and the fact that the waiter didn't let me know that there is extra charge for substitutions. 

I gave one extra star (3 was my original rating) because the left over steak (about 3 hours after) was soooooo good. And i didn't even heat them up...  

I don't think i would go back...  not because the food was bad, but because there are so many other options in town.

input_doc: I always have had a great experience every time I have come here! My friends and I usually come to grab some drinks and enjoy the live music they have. The food is always great as well.  Last time we came, we were celebrating my friends birthday and unfortunately it was the two weeks that Florida gets cold so we were not able to sit outside. We ordered a plethora of apps, such as the shrimp and lobster quesadilla, chicken empanadas, fire cracker shrimp, and cheese bites. We all agreed that the fire cracker shrimp was the best and we weren't really impressed with the cheese bites. Drinks are always good here, if you are not a big Rum fan, be careful because a lot of their drinks come with Rum.  I highly recommend coming here for just a fun night out with good food!!!

I love finding and supporting good local businesses whenever I can. There is a starbucks right next door, but I'm glad I chose this place instead. The service is good, food is tasty, and the ambience is cozy and casual. They have both indoor and outdoor seating (I sat outside since the weather was cooler for a change). The only reason I didn't give it five stars is the parking lot is waaaay too small and I had to park down the street. Their food menu is also really short, with only a handful of options, none of which were a salad. I ordered the early bird special with kale and apple jam. While I thoroughly enjoyed it, it wouldn't necessarily have been my first choice if there were more options. I'd like to come back and try one of their tea drinks!

input_doc: Came for brunch - about $36 a person (before tip) and well worth it. It's buffet style with every thing you ever wanted for breakfast or a seafood lunch/dinner! All you can eat crabs, sushi, shrimp, crawfish, pizza, chicken fingers, Thai wings, and for the breakfast lover like myself ; the best waffles (didn't even need the butter or awesome blueberry spread but it's worth it to put that on there too or there's strawberry) they had an omelet station as well as a salmon station with Fresh cut fish and beef. There was a chocolate fountain and all the sweets you can imagine (amazing cherry pie, marshmallows, pound cake, fresh strawberries and pineapple)  I am probably forgetting a lot. But all of it was scrumptious. Okay, the burgers here are exceptional!!! We came in for lunch based on the Yelp reviews and were not disappointed. We just got pretty basic cheeseburgers (the "petite" order gets you two little ones) but they were out of this world. Sweet potato fries were great too, the wings were good, and the service was great! Yeah it's a smoking bar, but they must have some kind of mega filtration system because we're not smokers and could barely tell.

Bathrooms could be a lot cleaner, and the music selection was way heavy on the Maroon 5 and breathy female singer-songwriters (it sounded like what somebody might pick for the soundtrack to a movie about a teen girl), but maybe we just got a weird day.

input_doc: This place has been in my bookmarks for a while and while in a post-food-coma, I decided to stop for for a coffee and sit (maybe sleep) in the sunshine for a little while. The inside of KDB is awesome because it's half coffee shop and half laid back office. Everyone in there had their laptops out and the tables were almost set up so that they could be used perfectly as a little desk. The best spot in the house is at the front where there is a little nook with two tables and a view of St. Charles. Despite how cozy and charming the inside was, I needed some vitamin D so I paid $2.25 for a medium (pretty large, if you ask me) chicory coffee and then sat outside for a while. Everyone here knows that people-watching on St. Charles is one of the most relaxing things that you can do and this place is just another spot where you can do that peacefully and without being rushed to leave. The only reason I gave them 4 stars is my fault- I should've gotten a more interesting coffee that involved steaming but I had just a regular cup o' joe. input_doc: So yesterday, the 90 degree temps kept me close to the office.  I was soooo hungry, but had no idea what to get.  So - I called up old faithful, I mean, Old Nelson and ordered a Cobb salad (a deviation from my usual chicken salad sandwich or liverwurst on rye) and it was soooooo disappointing.  I was hoping for nice thick bacon, but instead I got glorified bacon bits (not really 1980s bacon bits, but very reminiscent).  I was also hoping for a nice peppery ranch dressing, but unfortunately I got something that tasted like a "no frills" store brand ranch.  The chicken also left a lot to be desired, the seasoning was just off - too sweet, or too something.  Basically, my meal was tremendously underwhelming and after a few bites I found myself a little skeeved and peeved by the abundance of lettuce and shady lady chicken strips.  Old Nelson is so close to my office that I will likely be back, but probably only for the chicken salad sandwich on rye.  Or maybe, I'll just walk the extra block and enjoy a vanilla cone w/ rainbow sprinkles from Dairy Queen, that girl never disappoints!

input_doc: Love Fred's. I'm typically not a huge fan of buffets because the food tends to be mediocre, but Fred's is soooo good. Love going when I've skipped breakfast and need an extra big lunch. input_doc: I was REALLY excited to finally try this place and I was more disappointed than I wanted to be.  Our server was pretty good at first, but towards the end she was so scattered.  We ordered 3 appetizers that we were all looking forward to, but when our entree's came out she looked so surprised that we never got our appetizers.  She was gone so long that she didn't even know they didn't get to the table.  We all ordered bottomless mimosas and Rose.  It took soooooo long to get a refill we finally asked if we could just get 2 rounds at once.  They were also served in kiddie cups, literally 4 ounce cups.  The place was so understaffed that she had tables scattered around the entire patio.  I think I saw a manager helping, but wouldn't know who the manager was because no one came to introduce him/herself and check on us. input_doc: This was an amazing place. The Oceana Oysters were soooo amazing. You can never go wrong with eating seafood down south. We will definitely be back here to enjoy other dishes on their menu.

I wish I could give it a 4.5..

The ambiance is fun, low, romantic lighting with pops of red. Three floors of people watching. I felt like it was necessary to be dressed up; nice button down shirt and jeans for guys and nice dress or top for ladies.

I thought the food and drinks were all amazing, but I left the restaurant hungry, and that shouldn't happen when it is that expensive.

I can personally attest that the following are delicious:
Panela Chilean Sea Bass- Really well cooked with great flavor
Maine Diver Scallops
Beef Tenderloin
Chocolate Tower

input_doc:
I normally wouldn't write a review about a hotel chain, but the staff and rooms at the Embassy Suites NOLA on Julia St was sooooo great.  The COMPLIMENTARY breakfast was very good, and the chefs were very friendly.  

The managers happy hour for two hours a night was great, even if they weren't giving away free drinks!! We were really really impressed!  People from our convention were moving from the overpriced Hilton down the street to our hotel mid-convention!!

Great appetizers, pizza, dessert and service.  In the moment, I felt like I was dining at the best restaurant in America.  The fried artichokes with lemon yogurt were unique and delicious. The spinach pizza with garlic and balsalmic onions was unlike any pie I've ever eaten.  The smoky, puffy, crisp crust was sooo good.  The zeppole for desert ruined any fond memories of amusement park funnel cake forever.  Can't wait to return!

What have I been doing with my life? I'm now embarrassed to say that before trying Isabella's I would go to Baskin Robbins or Cold Stone Creamery to satisfy cravings for ice cream. Isabella's makes some seriously amazing ice cream. They have a flavor for any palate! The cones are just fantastic! I never knew waffle cones could be sooooooo good. input_doc: I have to make a pit stop here every time I visit!! It's a grocery store, not a restaurant, so be prepared to wait in line for one of their delicious muffalettas. 1/4 of a muffaletta is plenty for a meal, so I recommend sharing a half. There is minimal seating, but not to worry... walk to Jackson Square and sit there to eat. Sooooo worth it!

Mission taco's tacos are sooo good!! We went on a Friday night when they had $2.5 tacos, $2.5 tecates and $5 shot + tecate. 

I got the mango habanero shrimp taco, hot fried chicken taco, Baja fish taco and the BBQ duck taco. I always get the shrimp taco every time I go - it's my favorite; but the Baja fish taco is also very good and you can't go wrong with either of them. The hot fried chicken taco was also solid, and the  BBQ duck was okay in my opinion. I'd also recommend getting a round of tecate+shots for the table !!

Came here since I was in town for work. Was craving some asian and saw this asian fusion place and decided to give it a try.

The vibe I got walking in was that this place was fancy. Everything from tablecloth to servers coming and offering sparkling water to servers reading out specials, this was a fancy schmancy asian fusion place. 

Our server had some serious B.O..... only reason I pointed this out was because he came over and read out like 20 different "specials" so he stood next to me for quite a bit. I couldn't focus on what he was saying. By the time he read his 8th special, I had forgotten what he said for the past 3 minutes. It just left a nasty taste on my taste buds. not good buddy. not good at all.

Food. I got the golden bags since everyone seemed to rave about it as an appetizer and got the pad thai for dinner. The Golden Bags were good... but just good. In terms of taste, it gave you the illusion it was different and better because of the way it's presented. Instead of a roll, it's wrapped as a bag so the filling is more grouped together instead of spaced out thinly in a roll. So A+ on presentation. The Pad Thai was average. Let's just say it wasn't amazing. Would definitely try one of their other 20 items on the menu.

Menu: Uninspired $$$ American (there were very few Creole/Cajun dishes) Some meat in some boring sauce with a side of veggies.

But the question remains to this day:: how could the hype around such a simple dish so grossly contradict my own dining experience???? Chicken under the Brick, to me, was more like Chicken swimming in Teriyaki Sauce. The reduction might as well have been balsamic vinegar overloaded with sugar. Gross. The meat wasn't dry, but lacked luster since the sauce had not completely seeped into the meat. Without exaggeration, it wins the award for the most disappointing dish ever. 

The building that houses the restaurant is actually a renovated home on a residential block which affords an intimate and yet familial setting. 

My dining companions reported to have enjoyed their dishes. However, I don't plan on returning anytime soon...a contemporary American cuisine needs to create an innovative, themed menu in order to stand out. Dante's Kitchen, in my opinion, didn't.

input_doc:
Easy, free parking and a cozy Turkish ambiance.

My sister and I were seated right away. However, it took us 10 minutes to get a menu.... 

Two people working the small room - a man and a woman. And yet we had to flag them down for water. I was wondering if they were also partially cooking the food in the back as well.

We ordered the Appetizer Combo for two, the Bosphorous Special, a Chicken Kebab plate and one Baklava. 

Way.too.much.food.

Our waiter admitted it at the end, but I'm disappointed the guy didn't tell us upfront. 

Knowing what I know now, I'd skip the combo and go straight for the Baba Ghanoush, their best dip. 

Then I would share the Special with my sister and not have to take home (3) styrofoam boxes.... 

The Baklava was decent. Not warm and two forks only made it a pain to cut through. You need a knife for that one. 

I compliment them on cutting the Pita bread into bite sized pieces. The bread lasts longer for both the customer and business.

I take offense that the some of the bread was burnt black a bit, affecting the taste. Also, we did not get a refill of the bread when we asked.

I didn't find either waiter to be engaging at all. The guy stood an extra (2) feet from the table, made no recommendations, and honestly wanted to get out of there. The place wasn't packed, but whatever was causing his rush affected his presence and thus charisma. A little too soft spoken for my taste. 

The food was above average. Fairly priced. Light aqua club kind of music. Again, cool decor. I enjoyed the candy by the door. 

Yeah, check this place out. But be smart with how/what you order.

So lets start off by saying we had to wait about an hour and a half for a table.. didnt mind so much since it was nice out and we went walking around all the little shops.  So the second thing, all the staff are REALLY nice.  

Our order consisted of the following;
Mild wings
Small basket of onion rings, and sloppy fries.
2 small burgers
1 big ugly
1 coney dog
And chicken strips for my baby sis.

I loveeee wings, guess this was the wrong place to come to for my craving.  They were really juicy but lacking in flavor.  My burger was too... it needed salt.  & by the time I bit into the other half the bun was very soggy, not the good kinda soggy.. but just wet.  Not very tasty.  The mushrooms i asked for that they charged extra for.. they were flavorless.  & not to mention there was only like 3 or 4 slices of em on my burger.  

The chile is veryyyyy good though. If i ever come here again, i'll probably stick with that and some onion rings because they were delicious.  This place wasn't that great really. Especially for the very long wait!  Steak and shake burgers are tastier in my opinion!

Luckily for me, my companion is a master in Vietnamese style food and she knew how to properly prepare everything.  The reason this place gets a 3....the service.  Wow was it bad. input_doc:
I've been dying to try Bogart's, but every time i was near the joint, the line was always wrapped around the corner... Ain't nobody got time for that! However, I finally got a chance to try it during my lunch... on a Tuesday. 


The Customer service was good; the guy behind the register was pretty nice and suggested a side (the baked beans) to go along with my pulled pork sandwich. The inside is super duper tiny so either get your food to go, eat outside (if weather permits) or get there early!  The pulled pork was nice and tender! AND THAT BUN.......... DEE. LISH. Super soft and buttery.  The baked beans were delicious and the deviled egg potato salad was ok too. I just wished it was a tad bit sweeter, but that's just me tho! Their BBQ sauces were NOT a hit for me. Literally. 3 out of the 4 were BAD. Hence the 3 stars. The last sauce i tried & actually ate (it had a "b" on the lid) was JUST ok. That voodoo sauce was spicy as hell. They are a BBQ joint so I guess I was ready to be wow'd by their sauces. One sauce was so watery, I just..... Idk, but it was watery as hell. Lol. I would definitely come back and dine in so I can experience what that'd be like (& be able to order more food and not have to worry about falling asleep at my desk, hehe). But overall it was just good.

input_doc: First time trying and food was really good!!! Prices are great too. The only thing I'd complain about is there's hardly AC so you'll be sweating for sure

I like this restaurant , I really do .  I've ordered take out many times and the food has been excellent and the service even better .  UNTIL....
They offer an all you can eat , so three of us (all slender females who don't eat much ) decided to get it because it would probably be about the same price if we ordered ala carte . 
Big mistake .  The servers were incredibly rude , food came out all over the place with the entrees coming before the edamame , seconds were given the evil eye , and we didn't even get one of the items that were ordered and we ordered very little .  The clincher came at the end when there were four pieces of a roll remaining .  I asked if I could take it with me and was told only for an extra price . Understandable if we were over ordering , but in this case it was going into the trash .  So my recommendation ...if the restaurant isn't happy with all you can eat then get rid of it , and if you are the customer order ala carte .

This restaurant is quite hyped up, and was on Center City's restaurant week listing.  It had its good points, and bad points. I'll start with the good.

*  The food was quite tasty - my husband had the baby lamb chops, which were cooked really nicely with a subtle marinade. The highlight of his dish was the 'pear potato' - a deep fried mashed potato in the shape of a pear.

* I got the Iskender Kabob, which was quite good, but not what I expected. It's gyro meat on bread, but the bread is hidden under layers of meat and tomato sauce, and is cut up into tiny pieces so it basically dissolves by the time you get to it. The tomato sauce is very, very tasty, but the meal did not come with the hot sauces as promised in the menu.

* appetizers: feta cheese wrapped in filo was very good, and I'd recommend it.

*The Baklava was actually a really great surprise - I loved it (and I'm picky with Baklava)!

The bad points (ugh):
* The restaurant is painfully understaffed (or maybe it was just the night we were there?).  We had an 8pm reservation, but the hostess wasn't at the desk, and we waited 15 minutes just for someone to come and greet/seat us. Once we were at our table, it took another 10 minutes just to get menus, and another 40 minutes before they took our order! A couple who came in after us got their bread basket and menus right off the bad, making us unhappy customers. They just lack a bit of organization.

*The website promises free parking, but their parking lot would only fit about a fifth of their customer bank. So sad. We had to drive around for 40 minutes trying to find a spot (and the nearby parking lots were basically full) and finally had to pay $13 for dinner. On our walk to the restaurant, we were thinking, "This better be worth it...."

*The Sauvingnon Blanc I ordered was OLD. I know my wine, and this was stale. My husband's Johnny Black and Soda came halfway into our meal (we ordered it when we first sat down). 

I'm feeling generous today, and I realize they are a family run restaurant so I don't want to slam them. I'm giving them 3 stars.

input_doc:
Get ready to trade in your walker for an electric scooter, this place is coming back to life!!!

This was a Jonathan's on it's way to a slow and painful death. Being a building, it could not move to a retirement community in Florida. So, the next best thing was to bring a piece of Florida to the building. Jonny from Florida bought the bar and has started the process of transforming it into something nice. There are still some slow nights with the 30+ local barflys sparsely inhabiting the copius amount of stools around this large bar. However, the owner has done a few things to really bring the life back to this bar.  There are great drink specials and reasonably good pizza. Wednesday night is an ever growing trivia extravaganza. The guy who runs it is a tool, but you can still have a lot of fun if you go with some friends. Thursday night is karaoke night. There are some bad locals, but also a few that will blow your mind. They also have a singles night and you never know what new and exciting thing they will have around the corner. When you walk in, it feels like a Jonathan's, but pretty soon you will realize that this is something new. It may not be really good yet, but I have a lot of hope. Maybe in a few months they can earn another star.

This had also been on my bookmarked list for happy hours to try out in the city, so a friend and I came (last minute, since we found out late that happy hour was only from 5-6 and not until 7pm like we'd thought). I couldn't help but compare to Vedge, and even though Vedge didn't meet my expectations, I much preferred their food. We ordered the happy hour cocktail, a glass of wine, tots, pretzels, and peruvian fries to share. I was disappointed at the two happy hour appetizer selections, but the peruvian fries made up for them. Slightly spicy, cooked to perfection, I almost forgot that I had just previously consumed ..one...sweet potato tater tot for $2.5 and ...one...tiny prezel thing....for $2.5. To be fair, I'm pretty sure we paid $1.25 per wedge of potato, but at least the interesting sauce made up for it! 

The atmosphere is great and bartenders a perfect combination of attentive without being overbearing. Plus, the bar had enough space for us to sit and catch up without being interrupted or jousled, so overall a decent place to come for happy hour--but maybe not the overpriced food.

Luckily we had a nice buzz going by the time we sat down to our reservation on Sunday night, or I really don't think we would have enjoyed our time here. This place your typical old school tourist trap (white coats and tuxes for the staff; white tablecloths).

Our server was kooky (in a good way) and kept the drinks comin', which is appreciated on Bourbon Street. 

We weren't super hungry so we just did apps. The food was fine but nothing particularly inspired: 

DH hated his gumbo (it had tons of shells in it, but not much meat...more like a bouillabaisse almost) and my endive salad was fine, but nothing I ever feel I need to eat again on purpose. We found the Shrimp Arnaud over-sauced. The Crab Claws were good but verrrryyy greasy (too much butter...I didn't know it was possible!). The Alligator Sausage was ok but tasted so much like kielbasa that it really wasn't anything special.   

The space is kind of stuck in a (1970's) time warp and is packed with bachelorette parties (screaming) and oldsters (turning up their hearing aids).

It's fine if you're into this kind of thing, but I know there are better places to eat in NOLA.

input_doc:
08/11/2011 - 10:18 am 

For some reason I wandered off the beaten path towards the Warehouse District in search of this Magical Breakfast place called Deanie's Restaurant.  LOST!  I don't get lost easily cause usually I'm not looking for anything specific.  Epic Fail this be.  FOUND this place called Cochon Butcher open, empty and with the smell of sweet sweet Meat in the air. 

At first glance, I was curious at the Butcher section of various Meats in the Display Fridge. Premium would be the best word to describe it. With premium comes the associated cost as the economy dictates.  Obviously as a Visitor, I didn't intend to purchase any so TSA can make me one of their Canadian Bitches. Back to focusing on the Chalkboard Menu.... 3.5'd 

I wasn't actually reading anymore because I was starved.  I just wanted that Pork special you had on the sandwich-board out front.  Don't make me use my Grade-6 French on you.  Clueless still, I mumbled 'De lait' as if I'm asking for Milk but she understood.  Btw, she was cute along with a strong Southern accent. :D 

--------------------- 

Cochon de Lait Po-boy w/Pickled Cabbage & Buttermilk Dressing($10.00) 

Cochon de Lait was thinly shaved deli-style, quite tender as Suckling Pig should be.  Pickled Cabbage & Buttermilk Dressing kind of ruined the show although in their defense, it didn't cover up the Cochon's flavour as much since Cochon de Lait has lighter subtle flavours.  I was craving for some Crackling to kick-it-up-a-notch as another New Orleans notable would say. 

It wasn't all mediocre as there was this Yellow Magic in a Bottle on the table that saved the day.  The Red Bottle is typical Louisiana Red so I easily poured half the bottle of this Sweet Potato Habanero instead and used any leftover whatever to soak it up as if drinking Soup.  The mix of Sweet Potato and Apple Cider Vinegar gave it a Fruity flavour profile while smoothing out the Habanero for balance.

input_doc:
A date took me to Almond's last week and it was surprisingly slow (well, surprising to him, I had never been there).  I like the ambiance; definitely a nice "date setting"....dark, candle light, etc.  Our waiter was very friendly, although, almost in that "I'm talking in my waiter voice and this is not how I talk in real life" kind of way.  The menu was written on a chalk board on the table.  Now, this is a cute idea, but not very helpful for a "menu reader" like me.  I like to be able to read what my food is going to be like before I order it.  I realized I could have asked the waiter (and we did about somethings), but I wasn't going to sit there and ask about everything on the menu.  We ordered this risotto of the day, which was risotto was peas and tomatoes.  It was pretty good.....very strong parmesan bite.  We each drank a glass of an Argentinian Malbec and it was delicious.  I wish I would have known the name of it!  I had stalked Almond's on Yelp before the date and decided that with all of it's rave reviews, I had to try the pan fried chicken.  I don't get the hype.  To me, it was a glorified chicken strip.  I was expecting pan-fried chicken like my mom made, where chicken is fried in just a half-inch of oil or so.  This was so uniformly cooked, I don't know how it could have been "pan fried," unless it was deep-fried in a very large pan?  Not to mention, it was incredibly bland.  Even salt would have helped.  My date had the peppercorn filet.  It was delicious....although very very peppery.  I think if I were to return, I'd order it and ask for less peppercorns.  The meal came with mashed potatoes and green beans (which I remember being surprised about....until I remembered that I couldn't READ what came with the meal because there was no explanation on the menu).  The mashed potatoes were good and the green beans were okay.  Nothing unbelievable.  

I liked Almonds, but I won't be in a rush to return.  As pathetic as this sounds, I'd probably go there on a date again, but probably won't pay for a meal there myself.  :-/

I could give 4 stars because the drinks were stellar.  Everything else was just meh so I'm sticking to 3 stars.  The chips were fresh but so thin they kept breaking off in the dips. The queso, salsa, and guacamole were decent but lackluster.  The chicken enchiladas did not have much chicken in them and again just missing the mark in flavor as was the green sauce.  
Let's talk about the drinks!!!! They were fabulous.  The Pineapple Magonada was a delicious frozen concoction.  My hubby loved it.  I got the Spicy Peyote. I swapped the mezcal for silver tequila and it was perfectly spiced. I would not return here for the food but definitely would come back for the drinks.

input_doc:
Came here on the suggestion of our hotel front desk. Fun brewery in an old church.
Thought the menu was pretty impressive and eclectic. Not your typical brewery food (just different enough, in my opinion.) We were seated quickly and our drink / food order taken quickly.
I had the porter (only dark beer on draft.. for Oct, I would have expected more dark beers) which was a good standard porter. Little smokey, which I like.
I had the pan fried turkey burger with pickled veggies (cuddos on more than just fries as a side option!) Sandwich was good and the sauce had nice flavor. Pretzel bun was good! I couldn't figure out if the turkey burger was homemade or not.. it was pretty uniform for a homemade burger....
My boss got the pulled pork and fries and he enjoyed it, too.
It was trivia night at the bar, so we joined in.. because why not! It was fun, and got us to stick around for 2 more beers.

My only issue was the fact that both my boss and I woke up in the middle of the night with stomach "issues". Neither of us can say for sure it was the food or beer.. but it was an odd coincidence that we both woke up around the same time (which we didn't know about until the AM when we met up) because we felt sick.

input_doc:
This is really 31/2 stars. This is a very cute restaurant and a BYOB (both big pluses), with a looooong menu! It really is overwhelming! The atmosphere is great, it's nice and loud, makes you feel like you're somewhere more hip. 

But back to the food and the menu. It is one of the longest menus I have ever seen. There are plenty of things that look and sound good but unfortunately my immediate reaction when I see such a large menu is that there is no way everything can be fresh. They did have a specials menu that changes every day so I would suggest sticking to ordering from there, just to be safe! 

We were a party of four so we all decided to try a couple of different things. We ended up starting with the mussels, oysters, frishee salad and the beet salad, as well as sharing a small order of the lobster mac n cheese. I had the mussels, and it was a HUGE order of mussels with plenty to share between 2 people. The mussels were very good in a tomatoey-vodka sauce. I also sampled the lobster mac n cheese which was good but not as rich as I had hoped but not bad by any means! 

For our main I tried the "Fisherman's platter" which consisted of small samples of salmon, tilapia, crab cake, and shrimp. It was pretty good, but I wasn't sure how everything fit in together. All the components individually were good, and it's good if you want to sample a lot of different things so next time you can order the one you liked the best! I do have to recommend the crab cakes which was awesome, lots of crab meat. 

All in all we had a really great dining experience. Dessert was ok, all our our cobblers and pies were cold which was a disspointment but the ice cream was delicious!   The loud ceilings makes the dining room loud, in a good way of course! Our waitress was very helpful and nice as well which added to the experience! 

Lastly, I hadn't been to Phoenixville in a long time, and it truly is going thru a major rejuvenation. That being said, it's still Phoenixville....unfortunately. Give it another 3-5 years and I'm sure not only the buildings but the atmosphere will be just like West Chester.

As far as take out Chinese goes in this part of Philly, this is by far my favorite. But it's still not as great as some of the greats in Chinatown, which I'm using as a gauge. Prices are decent and the employees are always friendly. 

I've gotten take-out a few times since they opened when a hankering for takeout Chinese hits. They also have sushi....so the menu is odd in that regard. But the sushi is decent - fantastic but better than what I expected.  To be honest I've only gotten cooked rolls here as I'm a little afraid to get anything raw at a place that is not specifically known for sushi.  

As far as the Chinese side of the menu goes, I've gotten wonton soup, veggie lo mein and sesame shrimp. All were pretty good for take out. 

Big downfall is that they don't deliver. But a bonus (for some) is that they have beer to go (maybe that's why they can't deliver?).

It's good for what it is...fast take-out food.

input_doc:
Great place for happy hour, some apps maybe.

After hearing rave reviews and making reservations 2 times for this Mexican eatery, we finally made it there. 

The ambiance and location are great. Love the bar in the middle. Lighting and decor is awesome. 

We ordered macho nachoes which were really good. I ordered a Mojito which I have had better. I think it was a premade Mojito mix.

What was not great was sitting on a table near the bar and having folks' asses in our face all night. Had to ask a lady to move because her purse almost knocked the water off our table. 

Had to yell to have a conversation.

The entrees were were not so great and overpriced. I ordered the red sauce chicken enchilada that tasted like a regular enchilada smothered in Ragu sauce. I didn't finish my meal. My date ordered chicken tacos that were good but as they got cold the corn tortilla tasted bland and chewy.

Maybe next time I will order something lighter and choose an earlier time to be there. 

Anyway to request a red velvet booth away from 50 year old bar bros picking up 30 something ladies???

I used to looooooooove this place. I'm not all that adventurous with food so I will admit that I have only ordered the 'Chinese' food from here, and it has gone way downhill. I was so disappointed the last time my husband and I ordered from this restaurant. It has been my favorite since we moved to the area 4 years ago. 
 You know how the sweet and sour chicken is usually different from the type of chicken in, say, the General Tso's or Honey chicken? Not anymore at Egg Roll #1. It was all the same type of chicken, the sweet and sour type. And the sauces were very bland and just not good at all. I don't know where to get good Chinese food around here anymore! This place was my last hope after a couple unfavorable experiences at Great Wall. 
 From what I hear, the Vietnamese menu is much better. I will update my review if I end up trying something different. Maybe they put more of their focus on that menu since a lot of people come for the Pho and other items. I just want some good Chinese food  :(

Hmmm so people may hate me for this review...its okay I'm prepared for that.

So I have eaten at the other Sweetie Pies location a couple of years ago and I remember it being cool..nothing to write home about..but cool. Sooo this past Sunday I decided to give it another shot :-)

Here is my biggest complaint. The food was not hot!!! I mean how can food served out of hot pans not be hot?? I am very confused. Everyone that I was with experienced the same problem. I for one am a fan of hot food so I probably had an instant 'tude which killed it for me.

However I will say later that evening I reheated my leftovers and the food tasted much better. It was good. So overall, I would probably go back but just to get food to go.

input_doc:
Was here for a business meeting. First of all, the service was superb! Our server was attentive, knowledgeable and humorous. A+++ on the service.
The ambiance is okay, albeit very outdated. Their menu is daily, but I'm not sure what that update entails. Their menu online is identical to the menu I held in my hands last night.
The food... 
~ Clams were okay, but I'm not a big seafood person so do not take my word for it. 
~ I am a HUGE steak person and I can tell a good steak from a bad one by just looking at it. My coworker ordered prime rib, their special, and thought it was great. I ordered filet mignon bearnaise, which was ruined by the bearnaise sauce. Grilled to perfection, and then smothered in less-than-average bearnaise sauce, yuck! 
~ My biggest disappointment; however, was yet to come. Our server told us that the side dishes serve two, but then we received 8 asparagus stalks. This is NO joke people: 8 stalks for 7 dollars. Really? 
~ The Creme Brulee was delicious, although the caramel top could have afforded more time under a torch.
In conclusion, if they offered a filet mignon that wasn't smothered in that sad attempt of a bearnaise sauce and served side dishes that are actually going to serve two people, I'd give them four stars.

PDQ - "People Dedicated to Quality"?? or "Pretty Damn Quick"?? Whichever way you call it, PDQ delivered it BOTH ways!

I was torn between their specialty, the "Fried Chicken Salad", as well as being distracted by the "Fried Chicken Strips", and the fried "Thanksgiving Turkey Sandwich", which features real turkey and cranberry. Decisions, decisions.....I chose the chicken strips, and was not disappointed. They were delicious & crispy, lean boneless & tender breast meat. The breading they use is tasty and not greasy; I liked that my fingers didn't get full of grease. They came with shoestring French fries, and I had a Coke to wash it all down. 

I did like how their drive-thru works. One person is outside, on the ground, with a headset & ipad, taking the orders & relaying them to the inside people. The first window handles the money transaction, the second hands you your receipt, & the third, your food. It goes smoothly & quickly. Pretty Damn Quick!

input_doc:
Many would probably gasp in shock that I chose to have a pitcher of PBR at Dino's on the evening of my birthday.... 

What can I say? The previous evening's celebration was the polar opposite with an exquisite dinner at Silo followed up by bottles of champagne at Patterson and I just wanted (or needed) a change of pace. I had always been curious about Dino's and thought that on the first night of my much-anticipated stay-cation, a $7 pitcher of Pabst sounded incredibly welcoming. Boy, was I right!

Although Dino's is barely the size of a master bedroom in a Brentwood McMansion, it keeps character with it's gritty yet cozy ambiance. Think 1970's VFW hall. The bartender/cook/manager/waitress titles all belong to one friendly and efficient lady. The other patrons ranged from truck drivers to hungover hipsters while the Republican National Convention was playing loudly on the TV. Hot damn, I'm in the South.
(On another note, what was Dirty Harry thinking?!)

I had a great time chit chatting away with my friend who helped me guzzle the vessel of brew while an amused older gentleman watched in awe. He finally asked me, " Are you going to be able to drink that entire pitcher?" I had to ask him to repeat himself a couple of times as his accent was heavy and albeit slurred. Once I finally translated what he said, I smiled and flexed my muscle and said. "Hell. Yea."

Am I going to be a regular at Dino's? Not likely. 
But, I am certainly not going to hate on Dino either. I enjoyed my low-key evening of cheap beer, gossip, and politics very much. I'm sure that I will sneak back for a little escape when I have a hankering to do so.

I'd like to come back and try some of the bar food for appetizers and then perhaps heads off to Catbird for dinner. Isn't that what life is all about?

TIP: You can buy cans of beer here for cheeeeeap.

OK...I have a lay over in Philly. Two hour wait, excited to be going to Italy and eating all the pasta I can handle. I must first have my last American meal before going. When in Philly indulge in the cultural phenomonon called a cheese steak. I had a local experince with one of these little beauties,  http://www.yelp.com/biz/joeys-famous-philly-cheesesteaks-trenton#hrid:2uZh-dku02_iHRGrLV8HVQ/src:self, and I wasn't that impressed. So I wanted to give it another try along with a couple of beers. 
The cheesesteak I had was with onions and cheese, better known as wit and wiz....the cheese was a creamy white color not the usual orange cheese wiz with fries and a couple of america's famous Coors. The cheesesteak was steamy hot and the fries were hot. This was a pretty good sandwich, just not the best. It sat in my stomach for the eight hour flight like a rock. Unfortunately the cheese effected me and caused a gastomonic anomoly. Thank God for those overhead blowers on an airplane.

input_doc: Sad!!! My recent visit to Milk and Honey really took this place down a notch. Though crowded on a Sunday at 11am, they got us seated well before the quoted 1h15m. So I was encouraged that one of my fave brunch spots was still hitting it out of the park. However, once at our table, it was a real let-down. Our server was nice, but very crazed. Our initial drink order (which we placed at the same time as our food) took 10+ minutes to be delivered, even though I saw them wilting at the bar for nearly the same duration. Our appetizer took almost 40min, and entrees came another 30 min after that! Our server who was very sweet, couldn't seem to offer any reason for the delays. She just kept telling us it'll be a while. At one point, we asked for some toast for our super hungry son. We said we'd pay for it, but needed something to tide him over. She said she would talk to her manager about it (huh???) and actually never brought it to us. The food was all very mediocre, and the portions were tiny. Upon paying, it was a relatively reasonable total, but I wasn't blown away by the experience for the price. Milk & Honey, please get it together...I think you have all the good components in place. So staff up for busy days and get back to impressing us!!

input_doc:
Went here with a friend who loves buffets because of the value, and we had a coupon (of course). So $6.99 + 2 for a drink is still almost $10 per - not sure if the coupon was really worth clipping the coupon. 

We got there at 3:45 on a Sunday - since my friend goes there a lot, he knows the servers. His fav server came up and said she is getting off so good luck to us I suppose. We get seated and it took 10 min for our "server" (who really just brings drinks and takes away plates) to come and get our drink order, then another 5 min for him to come back with the drinks. Of course he apologized for taking so long, but really??? why??? you get drinks and take away plates. 

The food is not bad, with steak and a decent carver table. Much nicer than many Vegas buffets that are prob 2x the price, but they haven't been a good deal since prob the early 90s - I digress. I do like that buffet does not equal low quality all the time. 

So, I give the food a 4 or 4.5 stars, the location is about a 2 (second time back on the east side for me this week, pretty depressing :( at least the city is developing Eastgate some now and all the Superbowl money is helping develop 10 East) and a 1 for service based upon our particular server - left $1 for three of us.

input_doc:
In pursit of Vietnamese food in the Santa Barbara area, my Vietnamese friend and I hit up Saigon In and Out.  She grew up around Westminster so she knows pho.  I spent a month in Hanoi, so I could probably judge good pho too.

Location: Easy to miss on Milpas, keep an eye on the address.  Street parking in front and an odd dirt parking lot in back, look for signs.

Atmosphere:  Typical Vietnamese...clean, tables, chairs with rooster sauce etc.  There are some oddly placed large house plants.  Staff is friendly and attentive, no complaints.  Bathroom was clean.  

Food:  I've dined her many a time.  For pho: the broth is clean and flavorful and the meat is fresh, but sometimes lacking in quantity.  No excessive MSG like some places.  Nooodles are ok.  They don't have the usual brisket-flank-tripe combo but instead some type of meat balls.  I like tripe. The shrimp/lettuce rolls were good and fresh, but didn't seem authentically Vietnamese, but then again what is in the US?  Not for all but I like the corn pudding dessert.  

Prices:  SB...$8 for a bowl of pho.  

Bottom line:  #1 in SB area.  Better than Saigon Noodle, Saigon Express, and Asian Cafe.  If only it was closer to downtown or UCSB...

Their website is decent with a complete menu and prices.

input_doc:
Visiting a friend in Tampa and decided to visit, I had pretty high hopes for this place, it wasn't horrible but it's not awesome either.  The overall ambiance was nice and the server cool too.  We had:

The Cheese Board:  Cheeses were good, it was a very dry plate though; meaning it was very boring looking. It came with a small thing of honey and 5 almonds...thanks.   Also, if a table of 3 girls orders this app to share...we will need more than 5, super thin pieces of bread.  We asked for more bread and when they returned they gave us 5 more super thin pieces of bread...thanks again.  So we each got 1.5 bites and then had to wait 10 minutes to then eat another 1.5 bites.  We ended up eating plain chunks of cheese lol....They "grill" the bread...that's why it takes so long.  Once again, thanks for allowing me 3, 1 inch x 2.5 inches pieces of bread...please sir can I have another?

Burrata:  This was ok as well, not sure if anyone has ever had burrata, but when done right it's amazing!  This burrata was too tough on the outside, it was rubbery.  We didn't really eat it.

Tapenade: Not too bad I guess, once again, this quarter sized fried pieces of bread were given...is there a bread shortage in Tampa or something lol??

Rhubarb Tart:  It looked nice but wasn't executed right.  Rhubarb is tart and fresh, this "filling" reminded of the filling that used to come in those hostess pies at gas stations I used to get when I was 5 years old lol.  It was bland and felt greasy and oily.  The tart shell was overcooked and stale.  

Not the best restaurant, I get what they are trying to do with the creativity and all but the execution is just not there.  It's slightly off on flavor profiles and basic technique (buratta).

input_doc: We ate here with my family and it was just "OK"....we ordered the calamari and it was rubbery.
